## v1.4.0 (2026-06-19)

**Changed by:** ProjectAgamemnon extraction-epic #1 planning session — a months-old epic asked to
EXTRACT the agent layer into Agamemnon, but cheap existence checks plus a real build/test run proved
the move was ALREADY delivered under a different ADR/PR, so the correct plan was
verification-and-closeout, not re-implementation.
**Verification:** verified-local — the investigation procedure (find/ls/grep + `cmake --build
--preset debug` + `ctest --preset debug -L agents -L integration`) was actually run this session and
confirmed the extraction complete (586/589 tests pass, agents+integration labels 100% green). The
downstream PLAN was NOT executed end-to-end in CI, so this is NOT verified-ci.

### What changed

- Added the core NEW lesson: a large EXTRACTION/MIGRATION/"move X from repo A to repo B" epic filed
  weeks/months ago is the highest-risk class for already-being-done, because big moves land under a
  NEW ADR/PR that never back-references the old epic. Verify the premise before planning the move:
  run the cheapest disconfirming checks FIRST (`find <target>/src -name '*.cpp'`,
  `ls <source>/src/<moved-dir>` expecting absent, `grep -rl <MovedSymbol> <source>/src`), map every
  acceptance criterion to a runnable command, and build+run the actual suite
  (`cmake --build --preset debug`; `ctest --preset debug -L <label>`) to confirm "CI passes with the
  new code" is ALREADY true. The plan reframes to verification-and-closeout.
- Added the residual-triage lesson: distinguish residuals that MATTER (a moved type still referenced
  from actively-compiled code) from harmless ones (a `#ifdef`-guarded include, a Doxygen `@code`
  comment); a `#ifdef ENABLE_GRPC`-guarded path that the default preset never compiles is UNTESTED
  and must be flagged as an open risk, not claimed done.
- Added two When-to-Use triggers (extraction/migration epic; acceptance-criteria-as-future-work).
- Added Verified-Workflow steps 12 (verify-the-extraction-premise + cheap-checks-first) and 13
  (residual triage / `#ifdef` build-config caveat), plus a `# 6.` block in the Quick Reference.
- Added 7 Failed Attempts rows surfacing the reviewer-focus risks: assume-epic-unstarted;
  trust-sibling-tree-for-cross-repo-CI claim; attribute-provenance-from-CMake-comment (ADR-015);
  dismiss-failing-tests-as-out-of-scope-from-untracked-status; claim-complete-while-`#ifdef`-guarded;
  treat-move-byte-for-byte-complete-from-LOC-estimate.
- Added a Results & Parameters worked example (ProjectAgamemnon epic #1) with all five honest
  caveats (cross-repo Keystone inference, ADR-015-from-comment, 3 dismissed tests, `#ifdef
  ENABLE_GRPC` untested surface, 3,393-line figure not reconciling to 1,732 src + 4,349 hdr).
- Extended the planner decision tree with an extraction-epic branch; added a Verified On row;
  updated the Overview table (Date/Objective/Outcome/Verification).
- Frontmatter: bumped `version` 1.3.0 → 1.4.0, updated `date` 2026-06-15 → 2026-06-19, broadened
  `description` (added the extraction-epic clause + trigger 6), populated `tags`, kept
  `verification: verified-local`.

### Why

v1.3.0 covered already-merged fixes, uncommitted-worktree work, and the plan-artifact-shape lessons
(status note → Grade D; empty placeholder → Grade F). It did not cover the EXTRACTION/MIGRATION
epic variant, where a months-old "move X" epic is often already delivered under a different ADR/PR.
The Agamemnon session learned to disconfirm the premise cheaply (find/ls/grep) and confirm "CI
passes with the new code" by actually building and running the suite, then reframe to
verification-and-closeout — and to triage residuals so a harmless `#ifdef`/comment hit does not
inflate the closeout scope while a real compiled-code hit does.

